         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">14/11/93. ¶  ¶ It needs not my assurance, dear Mr Bastow, that I will give you the same full access to the Jungermanniaceae as to the true Mosses in my Herbarium. I do this with all the more pleasure,...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">93.11.14</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Richard Bastow</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M15, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">14/11/93.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It needs not my assurance, dear Mr Bastow, that I will give you the same full access to the <name key="Jungermanniaceae">Jungermanniaceae</name> as to the true Mosses in my Herbarium. I do this with all the more pleasure, as you are thus far an accomplished specialist, and as you evinced always a commesurate<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">commensurate? M had 'ss' and crossed one out.</p>
               </note> public appreciation of the the<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Word repeated.</p>
               </note> toils and sacrifices involved for bringing together such extensive collections as mine through a very long series of years (since 1847 here, since 1839 in Europe). I have given directions in the Herbarium, that due facilities are afforded to you there, while examining the <name key="Jungermanniaceae">Jungermanniaceae</name>. I prefer the last mentioned word (see Census of Austr. plants)<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Neither B83.03.04 nor B89.12.03 lists cryptogams, but in B82.01.06, p. 64, M uses <name key="Jungermannieae">Jungermannieae</name> for the leafy liverworts. Despite M's view, Bastow used the term <name key="Hepaticae">Hepaticae</name> in Bastow (1914), as he had in Bastow (1887).</p>
               </note> for the following reasons: 1, Most plants of this large order have leaflike organs, few only thalloid expansions. 2, The name <name key="Hepatica">Hepatica</name> was 1718 already chosen for the genus <name key="Hepatica">Hepatica</name> of <name key="Ranunculaceae">Ranunculaceae</name> (near <name key="Anemone">Anemone</name>), and 11 years later for what now is called <name key="Conocephalus">Conocephalus</name>; 3, the ordinal name <name key="Hepaticae">Hepaticae</name> was first used only in 1763 and included then even <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Marsilea">Marsilea</name> and <name key="Salvinia">Salvinia</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg>! 4, the name is misleading for the greater part of the order. 5, the genus <name key="Jungermannia">Jungermannia</name> was established by Rupp in 1718 and adopted 1729 by Micheli. 6, the ordinal name <name key="Jungermannieae">Jungermannieae</name> or a very similar wording was adopted by Gray already 1821 by Gray subordinally and by so many other authors; 7 the English word Liverworts is quite inappropriate for the vast majority of the plants of this order. 8, The well known rule can be followed in calling the typic <name key="Jungermanniaceae">Jungermanniaceae</name> as a tribe <name key="Jungermanneae">Jungermanneae</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <name key="Jungermannieae">Jungermannieae</name>?</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd von Mueller</p>
